'''Europhiles''' of [[Calcedonia]] lived during the [[3rd century BC]]. He contributed enormously to the study of [[anatomy]] with his many discoveries of the [[human body]]. He gave a detailed description of the [[nervous system]] and the connections between the [[liver]] and the [[small intestine]]; he also coined the word [[duodenum]] and established that it is connected to the liver through large [[vein]]s. He was also the first to distinguish between [[sensory neuron|motor nerves]] and [[sensory nerve]]s.<ref> Atlas of Anatomy, Giunti Editorial Group, Taj Books LTD 2002, p. 10</ref>

